1. Properties & Reactions

Properties of ACIDS

  • Have pH values below 7.
  • Have a sour taste (when edible).
  • Are corrosive.
  • Neutralise bases to form a salt and water.
  • Form H+ ions in water, making the solution acidic.
  • HCl(aq) → H+(aq) + Cl-(aq)

Properties of BASES

  • Have pH values above 7.
  • Have a bitter taste and feel soapy.
  • Neutralise acids to form a salt and water.
  • Alkalis are soluble bases that produce OH- ions in water.
  • Common Alkalis: NaOH, KOH, Ca(OH)2

2. Ions, Indicators & pH

The Role of Ions

The H+ ion is what makes a solution acidic.

The OH- ion is what makes a solution alkaline.

Ionic Equation for Neutralisation

During neutralisation, H+ and OH- ions react to form water.

H+(aq) + OH-(aq) → H2O(l)

Indicators & the pH Scale

Indicators are substances that change colour in acidic or alkaline solutions.

IndicatorColour in AcidColour in Alkali
LitmusRedBlue
Methyl OrangeRedYellow
PhenolphthaleinColourlessPink

Universal Indicator shows a spectrum of colours for the pH scale (0-14).

Refer to your textbook for the pH colour chart.

3. Strong & Weak Acids

(Extended Tier Only)

Proton Transfer (Br√∏nsted-Lowry Theory)

Acid = a proton (H+) donor

Base = a proton (H+) acceptor

Examples:

1. HCl + H2O → H3O+ + Cl- (HCl is the acid, H2O is the base)

2. NH3 + H2O ⇌ NH4+ + OH- (NH3 is the base, H2O is the acid)

Comparing Strong vs Weak Acids

A strong acid completely dissociates (ionises) in water.

HCl(aq) → H+(aq) + Cl-(aq)

Examples: HCl, H2SO4, HNO3

A weak acid partially dissociates in water (reversible reaction).

CH3COOH(aq) ⇌ H+(aq) + CH3COO-(aq)

Examples: Ethanoic acid, Citric acid, Carbonic acid

Comparing Properties (at the same concentration)

PropertyStrong AcidWeak Acid
pHLower pH (e.g. 1)Higher pH (e.g. 4)
ConductivityHigh (many ions)Low (few ions)
Reaction RateFast (high H+ conc.)Slow (low H+ conc.)

4. Classifying Oxides

Basic Oxides

Formed from metals. React with acids.

e.g., CuO, CaO

CuO + H2SO4 → CuSO4 + H2O

Acidic Oxides

Formed from non-metals. React with bases.

e.g., SO2, CO2

SO2 + 2NaOH → Na2SO3 + H2O

Amphoteric Oxides (Ext)

Act as both acid and base.

e.g., ZnO, Al2O3

ZnO + 2NaOH → Na2ZnO2 + H2O

Neutral Oxides

Do not react with acids or bases.

e.g., N2O, NO, CO
